Q1

Demographic information of the patients admitted into hospital is available in ADMISSION.csv. See https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/admissions/ for details of each field in this file. Summarize following variables using appropriate graphs:

  • admission year
  • admission month
  • admission week day
  • admission hour
  • length of hospital stay
  • admission type
  • number of admissions per patient
  • admission location
  • insurance
  • language
  • religion
  • martial status
  • ethnicity
  • death

Note it is possible that one patient (uniquely identified by the SUBJECT_ID) is admitted into hospital multiple times. When summarizing some demographic information, it makes sense to summarize based on only unique patients.

Solution

#Admission year bar graph Solution: Since the admission years are over the span of 100 years, the admissions are about on average 2 admissions per day. According to the training that was done for this class, the data span is actually over 10 years, thus the amount displayed should be 10 times more. On average, the admissions are about 20 per day.

admissions %>%
  mutate(adm_year = year(ADMITTIME)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = adm_year))

#Admission month bar graph Solution: The bar graph seems pretty consistent over each month. The average amount of admission per month is about 5000.

admissions %>%
  mutate(adm_month = month(ADMITTIME)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = adm_month))

#Admission week day Solution: According to the days of the week, the weekends in the first and last position are much less compared to the week days. Possibly, it could be related to work injuries or the amount of sheer activities that are done on the week days that allow for the admissions to increase during the week days.

admissions %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(ADMITTIME)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = wday))

#Admission hour Solution: From the bar graph for the number of admissions per hour, the highest admissions, about 5000, is at the seventh hour. This could most likely mean that there may be the most accidents when people are trying to get to work. Also, at the sixteenth through the eighteenth hour remains consistently high at about 3,500 admissions, which can also mean going back home from work.

admissions %>%
  mutate(hour = hour(ADMITTIME)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = hour))

#Length of stay

admissions %>%
  mutate(los_days = as.numeric(as.duration(DISCHTIME - ADMITTIME) / 86400)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = los_days)) + 
  geom_histogram (bins = 100) + 
  labs(x = "Length of Stay (days)")

#Admission Type

admissions %>% 
  group_by(ADMISSION_TYPE) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = ADMISSION_TYPE, y = count)) +
  geom_col()

#Extracted subject_id column from admissions #{r} admissions2 <- admissions %>% select(SUBJECT_ID) %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID) admissions2

#Extracted subject_id and gender from patients to merge together #{r} patients2 <- patients %>% select (SUBJECT_ID, GENDER) %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, GENDER) patients2

#Merged the subject_id’s together to determine their gender #{r} left_join(admissions2, patients2) %>% group_by(GENDER) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% ggplot() + geom_col(mapping = aes(x = GENDER, y = count))

#Extracted subject_id and admission time, also need to extract year #{r} admissions3 <- admissions %>% select (SUBJECT_ID, ADMITTIME) %>% mutate(adm_year = year(ADMITTIME)) %>% select(SUBJECT_ID, -ADMITTIME, adm_year) admissions3

#Extracted subject_id and date of birth, need to extract year #{r} patients3 <- patients %>% select (SUBJECT_ID, DOB) %>% mutate(dateofbirth = year(DOB)) %>% select (SUBJECT_ID, -DOB, dateofbirth) patients3

#Joined subject id, year of birth, and year of admission together, need to create new column for age #{r} left_join(admissions3, patients3) %>% mutate(age_adm = adm_year - dateofbirth) ggplot() + geom_dotplot(aes(x = age_adm, y = count))

#Create graph according to age of admission #{r} left_join(admissions3, patients3) %>% group_by(age_adm) %>% summarize(age_adm_count = n(age_adm)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = age_adm, y = count)) + geom_dotplot()

Q4

CHARTEVENTS.csv (https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/chartevents/) contains all the charted data available for a patient. During their ICU stay, the primary repository of a patient’s information is their electronic chart. The ITEMID variable indicates a single measurement type in the database. The VALUE variable is the value measured for ITEMID.

D_ITEMS.csv (https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/d_items/) is the dictionary for the ITEMID in CHARTEVENTS.csv. Find potential values of ITEMID that correspond to systolic blood pressure, i.e., LABEL contains the string systolic.

Compile a tibble that contains the first ICU stay of unique patients, with the patient’s demographic information, the first systolic blood pressure measurement during ICU stay, and whether the patient died within 30 days of hospitcal admission.
